					<td valign="top" width="2" background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tb_left.gif">&nbsp;</td>
					<td background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/trick.jpg" width="100%" valign="top">


<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%">
<tr>
	<td width="1%">&nbsp;</td>
	<td width="98%">

		<table width="100%">
		<tr>
			<td>
				<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="3"><b>    BlackSmithing Guide</b></font>
					<br>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">
					<b><A href="mailto:">Elindil</a> | 
		            8/20/1999 5:29:13 PM</b></font></p>
		         <a href="guides.asp">
		         <font face="verdana" size="2">Return to guide listing.</font></a>
					
					<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">Blacksmithing, hmmn, not for the one of shallow pockets. I can help you minimize that expenditure. I am a master two times over, different servers. These tips are definetly my opinion and if you choose to follow a different guide, do so. This guide is intended to get you to making banded as soon as possible. First you can be a smith with any intelligence but one with over 80 is ideal and over 90 woo hoo watch the skill rise. Next pour 20 points into training skills, any less and it takes more money and time. Next build up some cash so that you can buy ore in mass quantities. In Akanon with charisma of 92 and a High Elf it cost me 6 silver 3 copper per small ore. I would buy in 100 or 200 chunks so it would run me 6-12 plat. Next buy some water need that to make bits. Buy enough water for the amount of ore divded by two. i.e. 100 ore 50 water. Next find a forge there are three in Freeport one in Qeynos and one in Kelethin at least the ones I used. Drop two small ores in the forge (dont stack them) and one water then combine voila you get a bit or it tells you &quot;you dont have the skill&quot; dont fret at 20 in smithing your success ratio is about 50-60% and you dont gain from the making of the bits :(<BR>
After you use all the ore to make your bits by as many water as bits and prepare to do some creation. Scaler molds are what will take you to 41 in smithing. Buy scaler molds and put one mold one bit and one water and hit combine. The great thing about scalers is if you fail to make an item you still get a file which sells for about 8 silver that is nice, but if you succeed then you get a large lid mold sells back for about a gold, so it can really minimize the expense. Soon you will hit 41. Then the bread and butter of skill advancement, skewers. The procedure is the same as scalers, make some bits buy enough water and instead of buying scalers buy skewers. Dont get depressed you will fail and fail often and unlike scalers there is no return items for fails like files. This phase will torture your coin bag but once you get to 51 and beyond it gets easier. This training can take you all the way to 115 in smithing but hell lets make banded along the way to supplement our expense :) Make skweres until 51 then try to make banded start with the simplest to make bracers and sell your ware for 4 plat each that is a good price and if there is alot of competition try a pair for 7 but you set your own pricing. it cost about 15 gold to attempt a bracer. I always make skewers until 61 then make banded better chance to succeed. After 61 make some gorget and boots and keep making skewers those will drive your skill. at 71 make sleeves and helms 81 try tunics and masks. after 91 try leggings and mantles although mantles are hard at that level. After 101 you are master and can make mantles. Cloaks are damned hard to make and will give you problems well into the 120 and 130 so go easy on those stick to tunics leggings belts and mantles. well that is my rant on how I did it and in a relatively short time. I did spend about 100-150 plat but you recoup that on sales. Good luck to all the starting smiths.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
Elindil
			<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
					</p>
			</td>
				<td>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</td></tr>
