	<tr>
		
			<td colspan="2" bgcolor="#DEDACB" background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tb_beige.gif">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				Being a Master Smith on the Tunare server has prompted me to write this article.  I have encountered numerous individuals who tend to feel the cost of Fine Plate armor is high.  Then again, I have encountered a few select individuals who realize that making a piece of fine plate isn't simply a matter of running up to the forge and clicking the combine button.  To give you an idea of what is involved in that fine plate breastplate you are wearing or thinking of purchasing consider this.<BR>
<BR>
I auction /auct Taking orders for Fine Plate armor give tells<BR>
Someone says, Can you make me a fine plate breast plate? And how much does it cost?<BR>
I say &quot;yes, I can, the price is 15pp per AC, a bp is AC19 so that is 285pp <BR>
Someone says, WOW that much? Can't you do it for less?<BR>
I say &quot;sorry that is what I charge&quot;<BR>
Someone says, If I want that dyed can you do that?<BR>
I say &quot;yes I can dye, what color would you like?&quot;<BR>
Someone says, I want black<BR>
I say &quot;black is very rare and the components are hard to come by, thus making it expensive. If you want black I can do that but the cost is 300pp piece additional.<BR>
Someone says, LOL nm<BR>
<BR>
Now at this point you may be thinking, geeze.. 285pp for a breastplate and 300pp to dye black !!!<BR>
<BR>
Now I get to enlighten everyone on what happens on the smiths end of the transaction.  Let's say the above mentioned &quot;someone&quot; said ok, I'll take the breastplate but I'll pass on the dye for now.  Here is what I would have to do:<BR>
<BR>
First I would check my inventory and make sure I have leather backings. If I have only a few I then need to contact my tailor in Freeport and say,  can I buy a few more stacks of leather paddings?  He'll say &quot;sure, but I have to make them, get back with me later on today&quot; so in order for him to make them he has to go out and kill spiders (LOTS of spiders) for spiderling silk, then he has to kill pumas, wolves, bears and lions for pelts. Once he has done this he as to combine the spiderling silks to make thread, then he combines the thread and pelts to make leather backings. I have to get to West Commonlands to meet him to pick up my order.<BR>
<BR>
Once I have my backings I then go to Fewithe and buy molds, then head over to Steamfont and buy large medium quality bricks of ore.  This are very heavy (15 each) and I have to buy 9 bricks at 8pp each just to make 3 med quality folded sheets. That's ONE breastplate assuming I don't fail and have to go do it again. The breastplate mold costs 23pp.  So there is an average attempt cost of 100pp.  I have failed 3 times on a breastplate before and made absolutely no profit from it, on the other hand I have had success on the first attempt so it balances out in the long run.  So I take my large bricks of ore and go back to the forge in Kelethin, I put 3 large bricks of medium quality ore into the forge along with one flask of water and get one large block of medium quality ore. I repeat this two more time so I now have 3 large blocks of medium quality ore.  I then place one large block of medium quality ore into the forge along with my smithy hammer and a flask of water to get one medium quality folded sheet of metal. I repeat this two more times.  I then take 3 medium quality folded sheets of metal, one breastplate mold, one leather padding, my smithy hammer and a flask of water into the forge and click COMBINE.  POOF !!! Nothing. No fine plate breastplate.  This is about 15 mins after the &quot;someone&quot; said they would purchase the breastplate.  It's also about the same time you'll get a tell from &quot;someone&quot; saying &quot;is my breastplate ready yet?&quot; You explain that it takes a while and that you are working on it.  Then it's back on the circuit again gathering ingredients and trying again.  Imagine doing this for a FULL set.  <BR>
<BR>
Had the customer wanted the set dyed black I would have had to find the components for the dyes (charcoal from elementals in lavastorm) which is nearly impossible to locate. I fought in lavastorm for 2 days and managed to loot 2 charcoals.  The you have to find a shaman who can take the charcoal and make it into and extract, once the extract is made you have to find a potter who can make medium clay jars to mix the extract with resins to make the actual dye.  Naturally the Shaman and the Potter are going to charge you for their services. Then the dye has to be placed into the forge along with lacquer and acid and the armor piece to dye the piece.  I know a lot of you may think &quot;why don't you keep armor in stock and that way when someone wants something you'll have it ready?&quot;  Generally this is what I do and it does save time, but as you are aware the amount of available space Verant provides us with isn't much.  In addition to armor pieces I have in stock I also have dyes, extracts, dye components, leather paddings, smithy hammer, spare or extra molds, so you can see how difficult it would be to keep stock up on fine plate armor.  If you are a smith I'm sure you can relate to all of the above, if you are not a smith I hope that I have given you some insight as to what is involved and de-mystified it to some extent.  So the next time someone asks me if I can go less than 15pp per AC I shall refer them to this article.  I will continue to stand firm on my price and I will continue to offer free dying of pieces if my customers provide the completed dyes and I've made the armor for them.<BR>
<BR>
So, all in all Smithing is a fun and personally rewarding skill. Just be prepared to stick to your guns when it comes to pricing. What we do warrants every cp of that 15pp per AC.<BR>
<BR>
Stoan Coldsteel <BR>
Master Smith<BR>
Tunare<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>

				</font>
			</td>

	</tr>
	
